    'html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Most peptides in the nootropic space are single compounds targeting a single pathway. Cerebrolysin is different. It's a standardized mixture of low-molecular-weight neuropeptides and amino acids derived from purified pig brain tissue. This multi-component nature means it delivers fragments that mimic multiple neurotrophic factors simultaneously: BDNF-like, NGF-like, and CNTF-like peptides in a single preparation. It's been prescribed in over 40 countries for neurological conditions since the 1970s.</p>

<h2>What Cerebrolysin Contains</h2>

<p>Cerebrolysin is approximately 25% low-molecular-weight peptides (under 10 kDa) and 75% free amino acids. The manufacturing process (controlled enzymatic hydrolysis of purified porcine brain tissue) produces a consistent peptide profile that has been standardized across batches since the 1970s.</p>

<p>The peptide fraction contains fragments with neurotrophic activity similar to BDNF, NGF, and CNTF, though they're not identical copies of these full proteins. They're bioactive fragments that activate the same receptor pathways. This multi-target approach is both Cerebrolysin's strength (broad neuroprotective coverage) and its complexity (harder to characterize precisely than a single synthetic peptide).</p>

<h2>Clinical Evidence: Where It's Proven</h2>

<p><strong>Acute ischemic stroke:</strong> The largest body of evidence. The CASTA trial (1,070 patients) showed that Cerebrolysin added to standard stroke care improved neurological outcomes at 90 days. A Cochrane systematic review acknowledged evidence of benefit for acute stroke, though the authors noted that study quality varied. Multiple meta-analyses have found positive effects on functional recovery post-stroke.</p>

<p><strong>Traumatic brain injury:</strong> Clinical trials in TBI patients have shown improvement in cognitive function and Glasgow Outcome Scale scores with Cerebrolysin treatment. The CAPTAIN trial demonstrated improved recovery in moderate to severe TBI patients receiving Cerebrolysin within 24 hours of injury.</p>

<p><strong>Alzheimer's disease:</strong> A randomized controlled trial in 280 Alzheimer's patients showed improvement in cognitive scores (ADAS-cog) and clinical global impression with 6 months of Cerebrolysin treatment. The improvements were modest but statistically significant and persisted for several months after treatment ended, suggesting structural rather than just pharmacological effects.</p>

<p><strong>Vascular dementia:</strong> A Cochrane review found evidence supporting Cerebrolysin for vascular dementia, with improvements in cognitive function scores compared to placebo.</p>

<h2>Mechanism of Action</h2>

<p>Cerebrolysin's multi-peptide nature produces effects through several parallel mechanisms. Neurotrophic support through activation of BDNF, NGF, and CNTF signaling cascades. Neuroprotection by reducing excitotoxicity (excessive glutamate signaling), oxidative stress, and inflammatory mediators in brain tissue. Neuroplasticity enhancement by promoting synaptic remodeling and new connection formation. Neurogenesis stimulation with evidence of increased neural stem cell proliferation in the hippocampus.</p>

<p>The combination of these mechanisms explains why Cerebrolysin appears effective across multiple neurological conditions. Stroke, TBI, and dementia all involve neuronal damage, and the broad neurotrophic support addresses damage through multiple repair pathways simultaneously.</p>

<h2>Dosing Protocols</h2>

<p>Cerebrolysin is administered by intramuscular or intravenous injection. Oral administration doesn't work because the peptides are degraded in the GI tract.</p>

<p><strong>For acute neurological conditions (stroke, TBI):</strong> 30-50mL IV daily for 10-21 days, started as soon as possible after the event. Often given as an IV infusion diluted in saline over 15-30 minutes.</p>

<p><strong>For chronic conditions (dementia, cognitive decline):</strong> 10-30mL IM or IV daily for 10-20 days. Cycles are repeated every 2-3 months. Some protocols use 5-10mL daily for longer periods.</p>

<p><strong>For general cognitive enhancement (off-label):</strong> 5-10mL IM daily for 10-20 day cycles. Common in biohacking communities, though this use has limited clinical data compared to the neurological disease applications.</p>

<h2>Availability and the US Situation</h2>

<p>Cerebrolysin is manufactured by EVER Neuro Pharma (Austria) and available as a prescription medication in much of Europe, Asia, and Latin America. It is not FDA-approved in the United States.</p>

<p>The lack of US approval relates to FDA requirements for specific identification and characterization of active components, which is challenging for a multi-peptide preparation. The FDA prefers drugs with a single, well-characterized active ingredient. Cerebrolysin's nature as a standardized but complex mixture doesn't fit neatly into this framework, despite decades of clinical use and an extensive publication record.</p>

<p>Some US patients obtain Cerebrolysin through international pharmacies or medical tourism. Practitioners in the US who are aware of its evidence base sometimes prescribe it through compounding pharmacy channels, though this is an off-label use of a non-FDA-approved product.</p>

<h2>Safety</h2>

<p>Cerebrolysin has a well-established safety profile from millions of patient-treatments over 50+ years. The most common side effects are injection site pain, dizziness, headache, and nausea. Allergic reactions are rare but possible due to the biological origin of the product. Anyone with pork allergies should not use Cerebrolysin.</p>

<p>It should not be combined with other strong neurotrophic agents without medical supervision, and it's contraindicated in patients with epilepsy (risk of lowering seizure threshold) and severe renal impairment.</p>

<p>For neurological recovery applications, Cerebrolysin represents one of the most evidence-backed neuropeptide treatments available globally. Its multi-target approach addresses brain injury and degeneration through complementary mechanisms that single-compound nootropics can't replicate. The gap between its international acceptance and its US unavailability reflects regulatory framework differences rather than evidence limitations.</p>
